# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1830-belgian-general-election] Elections to the temporary National Congress were held in Belgium on 3 November 1830, following the declaration of independence from the Netherlands.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1830-belgian-general-election] The elections were held using a modified form of the Dutch system, as defined by the Orders of the Provisional Government of 10 October and 12 October 1830.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1830-belgian-general-election] 200 members were elected by plurality in constituencies of varying sizes, and suffrage was restricted to taxpaying men over the age of 25, with a higher tax threshold in urban areas than rural ones.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1830-belgian-general-election] Although clergy and academics were exempt from the restrictions, only around 1% of the country's population was eligible to vote.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1830-belgian-general-election] The order of 12 October 1830 distributed the 200 seats among the 44 administrative districts of the nine Belgian provinces.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1830-belgian-general-election] Along with these deputies, an equal number of substitutes were elected in each district.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1830-belgian-general-election] The Constitution adopted in February 1831 instituted a bicameral parliament, the first elections for which were held a year later.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] General elections were held in Belgium on 29 August 1831.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] They were the first elections to the new bicameral parliament created by the constitution adopted in February 1831.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] In the Senate elections Catholics won 31 seats and Liberals four.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] Voter turnout was 62.2%, although only 46,000 people (1.1% of the country's population) were eligible to vote.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] On 8 September 1831, King Leopold I of Belgium opened the 1831–1832 parliamentary session, the first ever of the Belgian Parliament.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] The electoral system was defined in the 1831 constitution and the electoral law of 3 March 1831.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] The 102 members of the Chamber of Representatives and 51 members of the Senate were elected by absolute majority in 44 electoral districts.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] Each district had between one and seven representatives and one to three senators; some were elected by joint or alternating districts.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] Eligibility vote was restricted to men aged 25 or older who held Belgian nationality either through birth or through grand naturalisation, and who paid a *cens* fixed by the electoral law.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] The *cens* differentiated depending on the place of residence.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] The 44 constituencies elected 102 representatives and appointed 51 senators as follows.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] Liège and Huy elected one representative on an alternating basis, beginning with Huy.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] Maastricht and Hasselt elected one representative on an alternating basis, beginning with Hasselt.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] This is the area of Luxembourg Province until 1839, when the stipulations of the Treaty of London ceded the area covered by the constituencies of Diekirch, Grevenmacher and Luxembourg back to the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] Bastogne and Marche alternated with Neufchâteau and Virton to appoint one Senator between them, with the first nomination being from Neufchâteau.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] Diekirch, Grevenmacher and Arlon together appointed one Senator between them, and a second in turn with the paired constituencies Bastogne/Marche and Neufchâteau/Virton.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1831-belgian-general-election] Philippeville and Namur appointed one further Senator on an alternating basis, beginning with Philippeville.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1833-belgian-general-election] General elections were held in Belgium in 1833.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1833-belgian-general-election] In the Senate elections Catholics won 31 seats and Liberals seven.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1833-belgian-general-election] Only 46,000 people (1.1% of the country's population) were eligible to vote.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1833-belgian-general-election] The Chamber of Representatives was fully renewed, following its dissolution by royal order of 28 April 1833.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1833-belgian-general-election] The King did so because of conflicts between the Liberal government (of Albert Goblet d'Alviella and Charles Rogier) and the Catholic-majority Parliament.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1833-belgian-general-election] The Chamber elections were held on 23 May 1833, with a run-off on 30 May.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1833-belgian-general-election] On 21 May 1833, just a few days before the elections, the government secured a significant diplomatic victory with the Convention of London, an agreement with the Netherlands to extend the ceasefire for an indefinite period.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1835-belgian-general-election] Partial legislative elections were held in Belgium on Tuesday 9 June 1835.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1835-belgian-general-election] In the Senate elections Catholics won 31 seats and Liberals eight.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1835-belgian-general-election] Only 23,000 people were eligible to vote in the election.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1835-belgian-general-election] Under the alternating system, Chamber elections were only held in four out of the nine provinces: East Flanders, Hainaut, Liège and Limburg.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1835-belgian-general-election] Thus, 51 of the 102 Chamber seats were up for election.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1835-belgian-general-election] The incumbent government was led by Barthélémy de Theux de Meylandt.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1837-belgian-general-election] Partial general elections were held in Belgium on Tuesday 13 June 1837 in which 51 of the 102 seats in the Chamber of Representatives were elected.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1837-belgian-general-election] Voter turnout was 56.0%, although only 24,526 people were eligible to vote.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1837-belgian-general-election] Under the alternating system, Chamber elections were only held in five out of the nine provinces: Antwerp, Brabant, Luxembourg, Namur and West Flanders.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1839-belgian-general-election] Partial legislative elections were held in Belgium on 11 June 1839.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1839-belgian-general-election] In the Senate elections Catholics won 27 seats and Liberals 12.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1839-belgian-general-election] Voter turnout was 66.4%, although only 23,661 people were eligible to vote.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1839-belgian-general-election] Thus, 47 of the 98 Chamber seats were up for election.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1839-belgian-general-election] The total number of seats decreased from 102 to 98 following the split of Limburg (its districts were reduced from Hasselt, Maastricht and Roermond to Hasselt, Tongeren and Maaseik).
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1841-belgian-general-election] Partial legislative elections were held in Belgium on Tuesday 8 June 1841 in which 48 of the 95 seats in the Chamber of Representatives were elected.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1841-belgian-general-election] Voter turnout was 77.0%, although only 24,887 people were eligible to vote.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1841-belgian-general-election] Under the alternating system, elections were only held in five out of the nine provinces: Antwerp, Brabant, Luxembourg, Namur and West Flanders.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1841-belgian-general-election] The number of seats in the Chamber decreased from 98 to 95 following the 1839 independence of the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg; its three districts (Luxembourg, Grevenmacher and Diekirch) had one representative each.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1841-belgian-general-election] The Lebeau Government, the first homogeneously Liberal government, resigned shortly before the elections.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1841-belgian-general-election] The unionist Nothomb Government took over on 13 April 1841.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium] Elections to the European Parliament were held in Belgium on 13 June 1999.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium] The Dutch electoral college elected 14 MEPs, the French electoral college elected 10 MEPs and the German-speaking electoral college elected 1 MEP.
[src:1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium/1999-european-parliament-election-in-belgium] The European elections were held on the same day as the federal election and the regional elections.
